Whatever this is, it'll have sparked your creative side, and it will be something you're quite proud to reveal. It may have something to do with the entertainment industry, or it might put you in the spotlight among your colleagues. You'll know with absolute certainty that you're not meant to fit in -- you're meant to stand out. Mercury Retrograde ends February 11, allowing you to make progress on a top-secret communications-related project you've been working on. It may take until the New Moon on the February 18 before it really gains traction, but know that this endeavor has everything it takes to succeed. Why? You have simply put so much careful thought, editing and planning into it. All of those hours behind the scenes will begin to pay off. Money flows after February 19, but so will expenses, so be sure to exercise patience and prudence when it comes to your budget. Hasty decisions about your finances might cost you more than you think, so take a step back and consider your options carefully before you fritter away any of your hard-earned cash. text: Mr Del Toro certainly creates very aesthetic and instant classic masterpieces throughout his film directing repertoire.....Crimson Peak however;..........with it's slightly obvious plot and rare glimpses of visually shock (accustomed to any horror); slowly reeks in it's own self composed odour of decomposing 'wasted talent'- Yes all of Del Toro's horrors are A) unique and B) highly character driven....but the delivery of this film confuses me - It's more of a period-drama than horror and in no way entices suspense or interest; held together solely on hope of some twist or underlying fact reveal, as well as the (quite simply) brilliant acting of the main 3 lead roles - I personally will stick to Del Toro's original horror classics and would encourage others to seek out more fruitful horrors such as Before I Wake, The Witch and even Maggie

text: Beautiful, well-crafted film. The story could have been a bit more layered, but a tale doesn't necessarily have to be complicated to be good. I personally really enjoyed it, especially the ending. It was incredibly fitting to the Sharpe siblings. SPOILERS AHEAD. Thomas, having redeemed himself through Edith's love, passes on into the next world (as seen by his disintegrating in the wind after his and Edith's silent farewell). Lucille, on the other hand, remains tethered to the house. She stays in the place that was both her sanctuary and her prison, unable to let go of the past. Ironically, she is also alone, the one thing she never wanted to be ("I was all alone. I can't be alone.").
